Exploring the Multilevel Impact of Information and Communication Technology (ICT) on Reading Achievement: A Hierarchical Analysis of Student, Home, and School Factors from the PISA 2018 Assessment

Nirmal Ghimire, K-16 Literacy Center

2024-08-26

Introduction

Information and communication technologies (ICT) have become increasingly integrated into education systems around the world. However, access to and use of ICT varies greatly between countries and schools. The 2018 PISA assessment provides a unique opportunity to examine how ICT factors relate to student reading achievement across countries, students access to ICT devices, their usage, and confidence using them.

Research Questions

Here are the research questions.

  • Student and Home Environment Impact: How do individual access to ICT devices at home (ICTHOME), perceived competence in ICT (COMPICT), interest in ICT (INTICT), and use of ICT for school-related tasks at home (HOMESCH) and outside school (ICTOUTSIDE) relate to reading scores (PV1READ-PV10READ) among students?
  • School-level Influence: What are the relationships between school-level factors such as ICT infrastructure (ICTSCH), resources (ICTRES), classroom use (ICTCLASS), and entrepreneurship tasks involving ICT (ENTUSE) on reading achievement within schools?
  • Cross-Level Interactions: How do student-level ICT variables interact with school-level factors to collectively influence reading achievement, and how do these relationships manifest across different countries?

Student Reading Assessment Data

The script reads another dataset related to student reading assessment data, summarizes this data, and again subsets the data to only include records from the same 10 countries. It then creates a smaller dataset (small_student) with a subset of the variables.

Variable Information

  • OECD - Indicator for OECD membership, dichotomous variable with 0 representing non OECD countries and 1 representing OECD countries.
  • ICTHOME - Index of ICT availability at home, continuous variable ranging from 0-11.
  • ICTSCH - Index of schools ICT infrastructure, continuous variable ranging from 0-10.
  • ICTRES - ICT resources at school, continuous standardized index.
  • ENTUSE - Use of ICT for entrepreneurship tasks at school, continuous standardized index.
  • HOMESCH - Use of ICT for school-related tasks at home, continuous standardized index.
  • USESCH - Use of ICT at school, continuous standardized index.
  • INTICT - Interest in ICT, continuous standardized index.
  • COMPICT - Perceived ICT competence, continuous standardized index.
  • AUTICT - Perceived autonomy in using ICT, continuous standardized index.
  • ICTCLASS - Use of ICT in classroom, continuous standardized index.
  • ICTOUTSIDE - Use of ICT outside of school, continuous standardized index.
  • W_FSTUWT - Student final weight, continuous variable.
  • PV1READ-PV10READ - Plausible values for reading, continuous variables (10 total).

OECD. (2019). PISA 2018 Technical Report. https://www.oecd.org/pisa/data/pisa2018technicalreport/

School-level Influence

Differences Between Schools: The random effect (1|CNTSCHID) in your model accounts for the unobserved heterogeneity between different schools within countries. Essentially, it captures the variability in reading scores that is attributable to differences between schools. If this random effect is statistically significant, it would suggest that the reading scores vary between schools, even after accounting for the observed predictors in your model.

Results About Students or Schools: The fixed effects (e.g., ICTSCH, ICTRES, ICTCLASS, ENTUSE) provide insights into the relationships between the school-level variables and student reading achievement, controlling for the nested structure of the data.

In the context of this analysis, the coefficients for the fixed effects represent the average impact of the corresponding school-level variable on individual student reading scores, taking into account the clustering of students within schools. Thus, the results provide insights into how school-level factors influence student outcomes, as well as the variation between schools in these relationships.

  6. ICTSCH: The effect of ICTSCH was significant and positive, with an estimated increase of 7.19 points, t(2.1710^5) = 40.94,p <. 001.

In summary, the results indicate that both student-level and school-level variables, along with their interactions, play significant roles in influencing reading achievement. The findings highlight the importance of considering cross-level interactions in understanding the complexities of ICT usage and reading outcomes.

Calculating ICC

icc = between_group_variance / (between_group_variance + within_group_variance)

Mathematical Expression:

1. Student Home Model

\[ y_{ij} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \text{{ICTHOME}}_{ij} + \beta_2 \cdot \text{{COMPICT}}_{ij} + \beta_3 \cdot \text{{INTICT}}_{ij} + \beta_4 \cdot \text{{HOMESCH}}_{ij} + \beta_5 \cdot \text{{ICTOUTSIDE}}_{ij} + u_j + \epsilon_{ij} \]

Explanation:

  • Outcome Variable (\(y_{ij}\)): The reading score for student \(i\) in country \(j\).
  • Fixed Effects:
    • \(\beta_0\): The intercept.
    • \(\beta_1, \beta_2, \beta_3, \beta_4, \beta_5\): Coefficients for the predictors ICTHOME, COMPICT, INTICT, HOMESCH, ICTOUTSIDE, respectively.
  • Random Effects:
    • \(u_j\): Random effect for country \(j\).
  • Error Term:
    • \(\epsilon_{ij}\): Residual error for student \(i\) in country \(j\).

2. School Model

Mathematical Expression:

\[ y_{ik} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \text{{ICTSCH}}_{ik} + \beta_2 \cdot \text{{ICTRES}}_{ik} + \beta_3 \cdot \text{{ICTCLASS}}_{ik} + \beta_4 \cdot \text{{ENTUSE}}_{ik} + v_k + \epsilon_{ik} \]

Explanation:

  • Outcome Variable (\(y_{ik}\)): The reading score for student \(i\) in school \(k\).
  • Fixed Effects:
    • \(\beta_0\): The intercept.
    • \(\beta_1, \beta_2, \beta_3, \beta_4\): Coefficients for the predictors ICTSCH, ICTRES, ICTCLASS, ENTUSE, respectively.
  • Random Effects:
    • \(v_k\): Random effect for school \(k\).
  • Error Term:
    • \(\epsilon_{ik}\): Residual error for student \(i\) in school \(k\).

3. Cross Level Model

Mathematical Expression:

\[ \begin{align*} y_{ijk} = \beta_0 &+ \beta_1 \cdot \text{{ICTHOME}}_{ijk} + \beta_2 \cdot \text{{COMPICT}}_{ijk} + \beta_3 \cdot \text{{INTICT}}_{ijk} + \beta_4 \cdot \text{{HOMESCH}}_{ijk} + \beta_5 \cdot \text{{ICTOUTSIDE}}_{ijk} \\ &+ \beta_6 \cdot \text{{ICTSCH}}_{ijk} + \beta_7 \cdot \text{{ICTRES}}_{ijk} + \beta_8 \cdot \text{{ICTCLASS}}_{ijk} + \beta_9 \cdot \text{{ENTUSE}}_{ijk} + \beta_{10} \cdot (\text{{ICTHOME}}_{ijk} \times \text{{ICTSCH}}_{ijk}) \\ &+ \beta_{11} \cdot (\text{{COMPICT}}_{ijk} \times \text{{ICTRES}}_{ijk}) + \beta_{12} \cdot (\text{{INTICT}}_{ijk} \times \text{{ICTCLASS}}_{ijk}) + u_k + v_j + \epsilon_{ijk} \end{align*} \]

Explanation:

  • Outcome Variable (\(y_{ijk}\)): The reading score for student \(i\) in school \(k\) and country \(j\).
  • Fixed Effects:
    • \(\beta_0\): The intercept.
    • \(\beta_1\) to \(\beta_9\): Coefficients for the main effects.
    • \(\beta_{10}\) to \(\beta_{12}\): Coefficients for the interaction effects.
  • Random Effects:
    • \(u_k\): Random effect for school \(k\).
    • \(v_j\): Random effect for country \(j\).
  • Error Term:
    • \(\epsilon_{ijk}\): Residual error for student \(i\) in school \(k\) and country \(j\).

These models reflect different levels of complexity, with the Student Home Model focusing on country-level effects, the School Model on school-level effects, and the Cross Level Model incorporating interactions and both school and country-level effects.
